The U.S. Securities and Exchange
Commission sued Johnson and Johnson for violating the Foreign
Corrupt Practices Act by bribing public doctors in several
European countries and paying kickbacks to  Iraq  to illegally
obtain business.  Johnson & Johnson (JNJ)  agreed to settle the SECâ€™s action by
paying more than $48.6 million in disgorgement and prejudgment
interest. Johnson & Johnson also agreed to pay a $21.4 million
fine to settle parallel criminal charges reported by the
 U.S. Department of Justice . The information was disclosed in an
e-mailed statement.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
